items.title: 'Door is open but I'm not looking', Ley says after Coalition split
items.standfirst: L iberal party head Sussan Ley says she is "absolutely confident" in her leadership after the Nationals rupture.
items.content: Opposition Leader Sussan Ley says she is "absolutely confident" in her position heading up the Liberal Party after the Coalition's shock split this week.The Nationals ruptured with the Liberals for the second time in just months over the government's hate speech and gun control laws that passed parliament last week.Nationals leader David Littleproud said the partnership was "untenable" under Ley's leadership.READ MORE: Three shot dead in NSW town 'related' to alleged killer, police say Appearing on Today, Ley said the Liberals had stood firm on their principles, including shadow cabinet solidarity."My focus is always on making sure we hold the government to account," she said."I've said it before, I'll say it again, the Coalition is stronger together."READ MORE: Iranian students in Australia facing 'darkest days' as economy hits record lowShe said the parties had a responsibility to work together "constructively, calmly" and claimed there was respect between MPs still."The door is open, from my point of view, but I'm not looking at the door," she said.She also dismissed suggestions her leadership was under threat, saying that the Coalition had "improved" the government's laws.READ MORE: Rose Byrne, Jacob Elordi lead Aussie charge for Oscars "I have led, and with respect, we've had genuine wins, with all of the things that we've done so far," she said."I am absolutely confident in the leadership that I have delivered, the leadership I will deliver, and the strength of effort that my party and I are making every single day."Rumoured leadership contestants Andrew Hastie and Angus Taylor were "strong, committed members of my team", Ley said.Littleproud told Today it was Ley who "broke the Coalition" by accepting the resignations of shadow frontbenchers who refused to support the government's bill.He also claimed the usual processes of party-room disagreements weren't followed."We are allowed, as a party, to have the courage of our conviction to stand up for ourselves," he said.And while the Liberals and Nationals were aligned on many things, he said, "there's this perception the Coalition is one party, and it's not". Nationals Senator Matt Canavan said the party had proposed "reasonable amendments" to the government's laws that were knocked back by the leadership. "My crime, if there is one, is doing my job as a parliamentarian," he said."I mean, what are we there for, but to make sure the laws that are passed in this country are the best for the people of Australia."He said Littleproud was doing an excellent job as party leader and that ordinary Australians didn't care about "drama queens" in politics.

clusters.neutral_headline: Police open fire in Melbourne after police car allegedly rammed

items.title: Police open fire in Melbourne after police car allegedly rammed
items.standfirst: One police officer sustained minor injuries and was taken to hospital.
items.content: Police have opened fire after a police van was allegedly rammed in Melbourne last night.Two men, an 18-year-old from Seaford and a 38-year-old from South Melbourne, have been arrested in relation to the incident.Victoria Police spotted the men driving a Jeep with allegedly stolen plates just after 8pm.READ MORE: Three shot dead in NSW town 'related' to alleged killer, police sayThey followed the Jeep until it pulled up near a motel in Dandenong, in Melbourne's southeast.When officers pulled a police van alongside the Jeep, it allegedly rammed the van. It also allegedly drove towards two officers at speed when they exited the police van.The officers fired two shots at the Jeep, which struck the vehicle's frame.READ MORE: Rose Byrne, Jacob Elordi lead Aussie charge for Oscars"There is also a Ford Ranger that we've seen at the scene with bullet holes in the window," Melbourne correspondent Christine Ahern told Today this morning."Police are unable to confirm at this stage how the Ford Ranger is linked to the incident."The two men who were allegedly inside the Jeep when the shots were fired were uninjured.They have been taken into custody to be interviewed by investigators.One police officer sustained minor injuries and was taken to hospital, where they are recovering.READ MORE: Iranian students in Australia battling to stay afloat amid economic collapseA crime scene has been established and Victoria Police are asking for anyone who witnessed the incident, has footage or information to contact Crime Stoppers.Professional Standards Command will have oversight of the investigation, which is ongoing.This is standard practice when a police firearm is discharged.DOWNLOAD THE 9NEWS APP: Stay across all the latest in breaking news, sport, politics and the weather via our news app and get notifications sent straight to your smartphone. Available on the Apple App Store and Google Play.

A man was taken into custody about 4.30pm and police taped off a crime scene on Jones Road. The emergency declaration was revoked at 5.07pm.There are no reports of injuries and investigations are ongoing.
